[2] Norovirus (Australia, NSW): suspected
Date: Wed 26 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Nyngan Observer, Wed 26 May 2004 [edited]
<http://nyngan.yourguide.com.au/detail.asp?class=news&subclass=local&category=general%20news&story_id=309727&y=2004&m=5>


Australia (NSW): Public Health Warning Issued for Macquarie Area
-------------------------------------------------
An epidemic of viral gastroenteritis sweeping the region since the
beginning of May 2004 has prompted Macquarie Area Health Service
(MAHS) to issue a public health warning. MAHS Centre for Population
Health has been notified of almost 300 cases since 7 May 2004, with
Dubbo, Nyngan and Mudgee hardest hit. Dubbo Base Hospital management
reported the facility's busiest day in at least 5 years on Thu and
Fri 13 and 14 May 2004.

Aged care facilities in the region have been particularly prone to
the virus, which is believed to be the same virus that caused the
temporary closure of hospitals in Lithgow and Molong in Mid-West Area
Health Service.

MAHS Centre for Population Health has urged people who have had the
illness to avoid work, child care centres and aged care facilities to
halt the spread. The virus is very contagious person-to-person, is
often referred to as "gastric flu" and is not related to food
contamination, according to MAHS Director of Population Health, Dr
Tony Brown.

The regional outbreak is believed to be part of a wider epidemic
striking many areas of NSW including the Sydney area with symptoms of
severe vomiting and diarrhoea. The number of viral gastroenteritis
cases usually increase in winter and are common within families and
group settings including nursing homes, hospitals, residential care,
childcare centres and schools."

Viral gastroenteritis is a common infection of the gut. The main
symptoms of viral gastroenteritis are watery diarrhoea and vomiting.
Other symptoms may include nausea, fever, abdominal pain, headache
and muscle aches. Dehydration can follow. Symptoms can take between
one and 3 days to develop and usually last between one and 2 days,
sometimes longer. The illness is highly infectious and is spread by
the vomit or faeces from an infected person by person-to-person
contact, for example shaking hands with someone who has been sick and
has the virus on their hands. It can also be transmitted through
contaminated, food or drink and even through contaminated surfaces.
Infection can occur possibly through the air when people vomit. In
most cases, because the illness is viral the spread occurs from a
person who has symptoms. Some people can still pass on the infection
without symptoms, particularly in the first 48 hours after recovery.
The infection can be prevented by washing your hands thoroughly with
soap and running water for at least 15 seconds and dry them with a
clean towel after using the toilet, changing nappies [diapers] and
before eating or preparing food.

There is no specific treatment for viral gastroenteritis except rest
and drinking plenty of fluids. Most people will recover without any
complications. However it can be serious for those who may have
difficulty replacing fluids lost through vomiting and diarrhoea.

