[4] Norovirus, concert-goers - UK (Scotland)
Date: Fri 28 May 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Press and Journal, Fri 28 May 2004 [edited]
<http://www.thisisnorthscotland.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=84106&command=displayContent&sourceNode=83936&contentPK=10128553>


Scotland: Concert-goers Affected by Suspected Viral Gastroenteritis
---------------------------------------------------
Public health experts today confirmed that more than 300 people have
contacted them saying they were suffering from symptoms of
gastroenteritis. The outbreak has hit fans who attended the
Charlatans concert at the Music Hall in Aberdeen on Sat 22 May 2004.

Health experts opened a phoneline asking people with symptoms to
contact them. Today they confirmed 300 people had been in touch,
saying they had the symptoms. The announcement means a sizeable
proportion of the sell-out crowd of 1200 have been struck down.
Scientists say they are closing in on the cause of a bug. The Music
Hall remained closed today while the venue was disinfected.

An NHS spokeswoman said that: "A series of tests have now been
carried out. We are expecting to have the results by Monday morning."
She declined to speculate on what the infectious agent could be -- or
how it was spread. But Dr Helen Howie, consultant in public health
medicine, said: "It may turn out to be an airborne viral infection,
which means it could spread very easily. It might have been
introduced by someone who was attending the concert."

The Music Hall was closed yesterday afternoon, and the entire
building is being cleaned with strong disinfectant under the
supervision of environmental health officers. The venue is expected
to reopen tomorrow.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[On Sat 29 May 2004 the initial tentative diagnosis of norovirus
infection was confirmed by laboratory tests. The unusual feature of
this outbreak is that approximately 300 of 1200 people attending a
2-3-hour concert in a large well-ventilated concert hall in Aberdeen
contracted norovirus infection, when there was no evidence of a
significant epidemic in the city of Aberdeen. Food/water-borne
transmission of norovirus infection can occur, shellfish being a
frequent culprit, although so far the local health authorities have
discounted this possibility. The preferred interpretation is presence
in the audience of a few norovirus-infected individuals spreading
this highly contagious virus. - Mod.CP]

