[5] Norovirus, hotel - Canada (BC): suspected
Date: Sat 29 May 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Yahoo News, Canada, Sat 29 May 2004 [edited]
<http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&cid=2155&ncid=2155&e=1&u=/cpress/20040529/ca_pr_on_he/parks_illness_outbreak>


Canada: Gastroenteritis Outbreak at Hotel in Yoho National Park
---------------------------------------------------
After more than 150 people reported gastrointestinal problems since
19 May 2004, federal health and parks officials are investigating a
private hotel in Yoho National Park. The investigation began after
complaints from people who had visited or worked at the Emerald Lake
Lodge about 50 kilometres west of Lake Louise on the British
Columbia-Alberta border.

The cause of the outbreak has not been determined. Officials are
working with hotel staff to identify the source of the outbreak and
to prevent further spreading of the illness. Symptoms include severe
diarrhea and vomiting lasting up to several days. It could be spread
through contaminated water or food or through environmental
contamination.

A boil water advisory is currently in effect at Emerald Lake. Health
Canada is recommending that anyone who has been to the lodge after
May 19 and has experienced symptoms see a doctor.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Norovirus outbreaks have been associated often with vacation
activities and places such as tourist hotels, coaches and ships,
where people from diverse backgrounds congregate with one or more
individuals carrying this highly contagious virus. The circumstances
of this outbreak are compatible with norovirus infection, but a
definitive diagnosis requires confirmation by laboratory testing. -
Mod.CP]

